### 3. Multiplane Quantum Internet Architecture Draft Update
*Diego Lopez* presented an update on the group-adopted draft, `draft-irtf-qirg-qi-multiplane-arch`.
* **Slide Deck**: [draft-irtf-qirg-qi-multiplane-arch](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-qirg-draft-irtf-qirg-qi-multiplane-arch-00)
* **Details**:
  * The draft proposes a general SDN-based architectural framework (leveraging the CLASS model) to integrate quantum communication into the classical Internet.
  * Recent revisions introduced a resource-facing abstraction called the Quantum Unit Identifier (QUI)—a domain-scoped identifier that maps to a globally unique Service Unit. A single Service Unit can map to multiple QUIs across space and time to manage state rebindings.
  * Additional text was added covering Quality of Service (QoS) parameters, OAM functions, and reference mappings for 10 analyzed papers across architecture, physics, and security.
* **Discussion**:
  * *Rodney Van Meter* noted that 13 pages of text had been added since the last version, making an immediate last call premature. He also reiterated that "forwarding" is not the correct term for quantum repeater-based networks and requested a wording change. *Diego Lopez* agreed to clean up the term.
  * An unnamed participant requested that QoS parameters be classified into topology constraints and per-request parameters to assist with network simulation implementations.
  * *Deborah Brungard* recommended using the generic term "optical networks" instead of "optical transport networks (OTN)" to prevent confusion with the ITU-T digital format. *Diego Lopez* accepted the suggestion.
  * *Wojtek Kozlowski* initiated a show of hands to assess how many participants have read the draft.

