### 7. Quantum Datagram Control Protocol (QDCP)
*Naven* and *Mitul Misra* presented implementation updates on `draft-zhu-qirg-qdcp`.
* **Slide Deck**: [draft-zhu-qirg-qdcp](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-qirg-draft-zhu-qirg-qdcp-00)
* **Details**:
  * QDCP routes classical metadata over UDP/IPv4 alongside quantum payloads. Metadata is structured in Type-Length-Value (TLV) packets.
  * The authors demonstrated a user-space CLI implementation on Linux that controls physical optical switches via Arduinos over SLIP (Serial Line Internet Protocol) connections.
  * Recent modifications refined polarization correction TLVs (adding "duration" and "arrival time" values to handle fiber distortion over time) and enabled time synchronization testing.
* **Discussion**:
  * *Wojtek Kozlowski* asked how the timing skew between the classical header and the quantum payload is managed at intermediate routers. *Mitul Misra* explained that the classical and quantum signals are sent with a designated delay; intermediate routers tap off a portion of the light to process the header on the Arduino, allowing the switch to reconfigure before the remaining quantum payload arrives.
  * *Rodney Van Meter* cautioned against premature optimization of strict bit-lengths (such as 24-bit duration) and suggested exploring standard formats like JSON, gRPC, or Protocol Buffers. He also recommended implementing IPv6.
  * An unnamed participant suggested using extensible TLV lengths (similar to Named Data Networking) to make the protocol more adaptable while remaining fast enough for FPGA processing.

